{'response': 'He looks at me with a madman’s eyes—
Fever-bright, wild with storm-tossed thought;
His gaze, a flicker of thundercloud skies,
Where reason and chaos are tangled and caught.
He speaks in riddles, laughter askew,
Words like shattered glass in the night;
Yet somewhere deep, in the trembling blue,
Is the flicker of longing for light.
I stand unsteady, a moth to his flame,
Drawn by the danger, the fire in his stare;
To love what is wild is to never be tame—
So I linger, half frightened, half bare.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'On the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword—
He cleaved the silence of the crowd, a truth no hand could hoard.
He did not bear the olive branch, nor gentle words alone,
But thundered through the temples’ halls, a kingdom overthrown.
His voice, a tempest on the hills, cut through the ancient lies;
He called the meek, the lost, the bold, to open blinded eyes.
A sword to sever chains of fear and pierce the veils of night—
He brought division sharp and clear, and hope’s relentless light.
So gather, trembling hearts and hands, upon this shaking land;
For peace is born through struggle, where the sword and spirit stand.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'On the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword.
He strode through shadows, fierce and bright, a fire in every word.
He shattered comfort, stirred the dust, and called the sleepers forth—
A challenge in His every step, a reckoning of worth.
No gentle lull, no easy path, but truth that wounds and heals;
He split the night with justice’ edge, revealed what darkness steals.
O, those who seek a tranquil road, beware His clarion cry—
For peace that’s forged with tempered steel is wrought by those who try.
So rise, O soul, and meet the dawn, though trembling at the door;
For on the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'On the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword;
He marched upon the troubled earth where silent griefs were stored.
His weapon was a word of flame, His shield a heart of fire,
He waged a war on falsehood’s reign and called the world up higher.
He cleaved the ties of comfort’s chain, unmasked the hidden wrong,
Demanded more than hollow faith, or softly whispered song.
His coming split the day from night, the true from what is feigned,
For peace that’s won without the fight is empty, lost, and chained.
So follow where His footsteps blaze, though storms may bar the way;
For truth and love are swords He raised, to dawn a brighter day.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': "On the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword.
He shattered silence with his word, and hearts with truth restored.
No gentle hand to soothe the pain, but strength to face the storm;
He called the meek, the lost, the slain, to rise and be reborn.
He split the night with lightning gaze, and tore the veils of lies,
Demanding that we set ablaze the idols we disguise.
His sword was justice, sharp and bright, a beacon in the gloom;
It pierced the shadow of the night, and swept away the tomb.
So do not seek a tranquil path, or comfort's easy chair;
For Christ the Lord, with holy wrath, bids us to act, to dare.", 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;  
In silent dawn and midnight deep,  
Thy presence fills my heart of stone,  
Thy promise guards me as I sleep.  
When shadows fall and hope is thin,  
Within my soul Thy light is sown;  
No earthly power, nor mortal kin,  
Can claim the love that is Thine own.

Upon the winds my prayers are flown,  
Across the wild and restless sea;  
O God! Thou art my God alone—  
Forever near, sustaining me.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;  
In every breath, Thy name I find.  
Through tempests wild, through joy unknown,  
Thy whisper calms my restless mind.  
The stars, ablaze, proclaim Thy grace,  
The river’s song recites Thy truth;  
In sacred silence, time and space  
Are stitched together by Thy proof.

No idol’s charm, no fleeting throne,  
Could draw my longing heart from Thee;  
O God! Thou art my God alone—  
My refuge for eternity.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;  
My wandering soul returns to Thee.  
Through desert winds and tempests blown,  
Your steadfast love has sheltered me.  
No golden calf, no marble throne,  
Could take the place You hold inside;  
You claim my heart, You call Your own,  
And in Your shadow I abide.

With trembling lips, my prayer is shown—  
A song of longing, trust, and awe.  
O God! Thou art my God alone;  
My hope, my strength, my guiding law.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;
In silent dawns when hope is frail,
My spirit seeks Thy gentle throne,
A weary heart, a whispered tale.
Through shadowed vale and trembling night,
I lift my soul in prayer and song;
For in Thy love, the world is light,
And in Thy arms, I do belong.
No idol voice nor fleeting star
Can claim the faith that’s Yours to own;
My every breath, both near and far,
Cries out, O God! Thou art my God alone.

', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;
Upon the winds my longing flies,
To seek Thy presence, pure, unknown,
Beyond the bounds of earthly skies.
No crafted form nor gilded creed
Can hold the depth of love I feel;
My soul, in silent, urgent need,
Finds only Thee to trust and heal.
Through tempests wild or sunlit peace,
My heart remains Thy dwelling place;
O God, my doubts and fears release,
And show me once again Thy face.

', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'O God! Thou art my God alone;
Amid the clamor of the day,
When fleeting joys and sorrows groan,
I pause my heart, I kneel, I pray.
No mortal hand nor fleeting fame
Can claim the worship that is Thine;
In sacred hush I praise Thy name,
And drink the depths of love divine.
Though shadows cross and burdens press,
Thy steadfast grace remains my own;
In every trial, I confess,
O God! Thou art my God alone.

', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'A hush before the lark’s first song,
Where shadows stretch and day is long;
The scent of ink, of grass, of books,
A world of secrets, sideways looks.

The echo of a distant bell,
A silent pact no tongue will tell;
The laughter, sharp as flint and flame,
A prelude to a wilder game.

Here, in the quiet, boys conspire,
Their hearts alight with fierce desire;
To test the rules, to bend, to break,
To find what worlds their wits can make.

So turn the page, and let them go—
To chase the winds, to steal the show;
For here begins, in whispered low,
The legend: Stalky & Co.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Before the plot, the cricket pitch,
The scent of chalk and summer’s wish;
A prelude painted soft and slow,
Where dreams of mischief start to grow.

The dormitory’s muffled cheer,
The plotting eyes that glisten clear;
A world contained in schoolyard bounds,
Yet vast where youthful hope resounds.

A friendship forged in sly exchange,
Of plans both intricate and strange;
This is the dawn, the opening scene,
Of laughter sharp and pranks unseen.

Prelude to Stalky and his crew—
A promise of what boys will do;
In every shadow, every jest,
The heart of youth is manifest.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': "Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
The silver puddles on the street;
Let every splash—a moment missed—
Remind you joy is fleet of feet.
Chase after crows with wild delight,
And twirl beneath the thunder's drum;
Your laughter, bright as morning light,
Will call the bashful rain to come.
So kiss the world, both near and far,
With lips unburdened by regret;
For in your wake, like falling stars,
The world remembers not to fret.", 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'My poem may be yours indeed;
Take it, wear it like the rain—
Let it soften every need,
Mingle joy with gentle pain.
Let its rhythm guide your feet
Down the halls of memory;
In every stanza, you may meet
A shadow or a reverie.
Though the ink was mine to spill,
Now the meaning’s yours to lead;
Let your longing, heart, and will—
Claim my poem, yours indeed.

', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': "Soldier, wake—the day is peeping,
Softly through the misted haze;
Silent prayers the stars were keeping
Fade beneath the sun's first rays.
The earth is hush, the world is waiting,
For your footfall, brave and sure;
In every breath, a hope creating,
In every step, resolve so pure.
Rise to meet the morning’s wonder,
Let the light your spirit fill;
Though the cannons roar like thunder,
Hold your ground, remain steadfast still.
Soldier, wake—the day is peeping,
With the dawn, your journey starts;
Carry honor in your keeping,
And the courage of a thousand hearts.", 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'Farewell, thou child of my right hand, and joy;
In tender arms once nestled, now released,
Your laughter, like a bell, no longer buoy;
The garden’s bloom is spent, the songbird ceased.
Yet in the hush that follows sorrow’s tread,
Your memory kindles hope within the gloom.
A gentle star above my sleepless bed,
A secret fragrance in an empty room.
Though fate’s stern hand has parted us apart,
Your name endures within my trembling heart.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'We sink into the dust, our names a whispered song,
Carried by the vagrant wind that trails the dusk along.
Time, the silent architect, builds monuments of bone;
Yet in the soil’s embrace, our spirits are not alone.
Each grain remembers sunlight, each shadow shapes the dawn—
We sink, but in the sinking, the world is newly drawn.', 'probability': 1.0}

{'response': 'As less on earth seek truth above,
A hush falls softly on the land;
The stars peer down, unheeded love,
While dreams slip gently from the hand.
The questions fade in city lights,
Where silent yearning fills the air;
Yet in the dusk of lonely nights,
Some hearts still whisper ancient prayer.
For truth, elusive as the mist,
Still waits beyond our mortal view;
And those who dare to hope, persist—
To search, to wonder, to renew.', 'probability': 1.0}
